### What are Services?

Services are singleton objects that encapsulate reusable business logic, data access, or cross-cutting concerns (logging, caching, authentication).

### @Injectable Decorator

Use `@Injectable` to make a class available for dependency injection:

```typescript
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class DataService {
  private data: string[] = [];

  getData(): string[] {
    return this.data;
  }

  addData(item: string): void {
    this.data.push(item);
  }
}
```

`providedIn: 'root'` registers the service with the **root injector**, making it available application-wide as a singleton.

### Providing Services

You can register services at different levels:

```typescript
// 1. Root level (singleton across the app)
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })

// 2. Module level (available within a module)
@NgModule({
  providers: [UserService]
})

// 3. Component level (new instance per component)
@Component({
  providers: [LoggerService]
})
```

### Provider Configurations

Angular's DI supports multiple provider types:

```typescript
// Class provider (default)
{ provide: LoggerService, useClass: LoggerService }

// Alternative class
{ provide: LoggerService, useClass: AdvancedLoggerService }

// Value provider
{ provide: 'API_URL', useValue: 'https://api.example.com' }

// Factory provider
{ provide: 'LOGGER', useFactory: (config) => {
  return config.debug ? new DebugLogger() : new LoggerService();
}, deps: [AppConfig] }
```

### Using Services in Components

Inject services via constructor:

```typescript
@Component({...})
export class UserComponent {
  constructor(private dataService: DataService) { }

  loadData() {
    this.items = this.dataService.getData();
  }
}
```

### Hierarchical Injectors

Angular has a **hierarchical DI system**. When a component requests a service, Angular looks up the injector tree:

1. Component's own injector
2. Parent component's injector
3. Module injector
4. Root injector

Services provided at a lower level **shadow** those from higher levels. This allows scoped service instances (e.g., a new instance for each component).

codeExample:
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class UserService {
  private users: User[] = [];

  getUsers(): Observable<User[]> {
    return of(this.users);
  }

  addUser(user: User): void {
    this.users.push(user);
  }
}

// Inject in component
@Component({...})
export class UsersComponent {
  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}
}
